“Either I’m perfect or I’m not”. When it comes to the holiday season it can feel like all or nothing. Either you’re on track with your workouts or one holiday part throws you off your schedule for the whole workout. Here are my three tips for overcoming this mindset and avoiding health debt this holiday season!

1. Make your life NEAT!!
NEAT stands for Non-exercise activity thermogenesis aka a way to burn calories outside of a typical workout. People who move inadvertently through out the day are better at maintaining ways.
Find ways to pepper movement through your day, take a second to dance, roll your shoulders at your desk, just generally keep moving when you can! Make your everyday a little bit more energetic!!

2. During those holiday parties, make sure to keep my “Love It” rule in mind. If you want to eat outside your typical diet, make sure it’s something you love!!! There’s so many sweets during the holidays, make sure if you indulge, it’s worth it!!

3. Use the “fresh start” effect! December 31st is just as much your life as January 1st. Embrace a mindset of “course correction”! Make any moment a fresh start and course correct ASAP. Maybe you went out Saturday night, make Sunday morning your fresh start, not Monday! James Clear says “Never Miss Twice”. Missing one workout is life, but two misses is the start of a new habit.

For more check out the link in my bio!!!

We're doing a PRI Aductor Pullback today. Setupis really important for sthis one.
Find a wall.
Lie on the floor on your side with your knees bent at a 90° angle and your feet planted on the wall as if you were standing with your heel and toes pressed to the wall.
Put something between your knees that has a similar thickness to a foam roller. Keep your top leg at hip height.
Keep a little pelvic tuck so you are not arching your back. Keep your ribs connected so you are working through your core.
Start with some breathing. Breath into your back ribs. Send air down to your pelvis so your diaphragm is descending down. 
As you exhale you are keeping your core connected and now pull your top thigh bone back using your glute muscles and your inner thigh abductors.

If you are having trouble connecting your to your glute or inner thigh muscles use your hand for tactile feedback.

Try doing this 4 or 5 times and then switch sides.

Enjoy!

Today we’re going to do some more pelvic floor breathing - but with a twist! I am using the stability ball as it gives great feedback.
Put your ball against a wall.
Kneel on your hands and knees and press your sit bones into the ball.
Take a deep breath.
When you breath in I want you to feel your sit bones widen out as you feel the air go into your pelvis. (It doesn’t ACTUALLY go to your pelvis. As your diaphragm descends down it pushes down your gut so that your sit bones widen and open up.)

As you exhale you connect and contract. Breath out to a count of three. Firm up your abdomen. Concentrate on 1) your pelvic bone right at the pubic bone 2) your lower abdominals - at the “smile” near your hips3) your belly button to spine. Another way to this of it is an elevator going up.

No arching. Keep your head in line with your spine.

Don’t turn on like a 10 out of 10. Keep at a 3 out of 10. This is a more relaxed movement.

I’ve got the 3 keys 🔑 to staying on track during the holiday season… here they are!!

1. Never miss two workouts. If you miss one workout that’s fine, but don’t make it a habit! Make sure you hop right back on that fitness horse and make time for your next workout!

Today we are doing the single arm farmer’s march. It’s a little tweek of the farmer’s carry in which you walk while a carrying something heavy while trying to keep your posture. I like this exercise as it gives you more of an opportunity to look at your form.

To begin, look in a mirror to see what your natural posture is. For most of us we have one shoulder that is lower than the other. See where you bias. Does your left hip jut out? Your right shoulder lower?

Bend over and pick up your weight. Continue looking in the mirror and raise one knee up and slowly march in place. While you raise each leg make sure you keep your shoulders straight. Repeat 8 times.

Once you feel like you can do this easily progress to the farmer’s carry.

Enjoy!

Happy 2023!!! Here’s your first Monday Moves of the year and today I’m going to take you through some variations on the figure 4 stretch. 

Option 1: Lying on floor
Lie down on your back with your knees raised and feet on the ground.

Variation #1
* Put your left ankle on your right knee (this puts your left leg in a figure 4 position)
* Gentle press away on your left knee. Keep neutral through your pelvis and try not to shift your hips.
* Hold for 30 seconds.
* Repeat with right ankle, or progress to variation #2.

Variation #2
* Raise your right leg and circle your hamstring with your right arm. 
* Pull your legs towards your body while you press gently on your left knee with your left hand . 
* You can use a band if your arms are not long enough to circle your legs. 
* Hold for 30 seconds. 

Variation #3
* You can follow either of these with a “lady stretch”, where your legs are fully crossed as you bring them in close to your body. 
* Hold for 30 seconds.
* Repeat with other leg.

Option 2: Sitting on floor
Variation #1
* Sit on the floor with your knees raised and your feet In full contact with the floor. Make sure the ball of your big toe and the ball of your little toe are equally weighted.
* Lean back on your hands and place your left ankle on your right knee as you did above. Then use your hands to press your upper body up towards your knees. This is good because it helps you get extension in your spine. Sit tall. If you are finding you are rounding you can sit on a pillow and/or move your right foot out.
* Repeat on the opposite side.

 BREATHE!

Today we’re going to do some variations on the Seated Figure 4. This is an awesome stretch. Added bonus — if you sit a lot at work, you’re already seated and can do these right at your desk!

Starting position:
* Take your ankle and place it on your opposite thigh. Make sure it’s your ankle NOT YOUR FOOT. That way you don’t warp your ankle. 
* Sit tall. Imagine your head is hooked to the ceiling g and it’s pulling you taller. 
* Keep your core engaged.
* Put your hand on your thigh and sit in the breath.
* Switch legs.

Add Dynamics to the stretch:
* Hinge forward over your foot, over your shin and over your knee
* Make sure you are not rounding your back. Think about your breastbone being pulled forward.
* After doing the hinge you can go back and “sit in the stretch” in any place that felt extra tight.
* Switch legs.
* It’s a great time to give your ankles some love. Grab your ankle and rotate and follow with flexing back and forth.

FEELS SO GOOD!!!

Enjoy! See you next Monday!

Today I’m going to show you the De-lift with banded variations. 

If you haven’t watched the original video, you can find them on my page.

* Put your band around your ankles.
* Lie down on your side as if you were lying against a wall. Keep your shoulders, hips and your feet all aligned against that imaginary wall.
* Don’t roll forward or backward - keep your body at 90° to the floor. Keep your hips level to one another. You can keep your bottom leg bent for balance if needed.
* Put your hand on the side of the hip that is on top. This is the muscle you are going to be working.
* Engage your core. Keep your ribs nice and knitted so you aren’t arching your back.
* Place your hand on your hip.
* Lift up slowly with control from the side of your leg. 
* Slowly lower down.
* Repeat and then switch sides. 

And., why not try the de-lift. Instead of lowering your leg:
* Put your hand on the back of your butt and move your leg back and around. Make sure you are using your glutes so you don’t strain your back.

* Think like you are moving through mud. Work against it.
* Repeat and then switch sides. 

TIP! Try these in front of a mirror. It will significantly help you with your form!

Today we are going to do a variation on the Bird Dog that I like to call the 13-3-6. 

Follow these rules and you’re all set to reap the rewards of this challenging exercise.

When you move your hands or arms while the band is wrapped around your wrist, move from your armpits and really feel the connection of your armpits into your core. No yanking of your wrist, elbow or neck!

This is a great exercise if you do it properly! 
- Wrap your band around your wrists.
- Go on your hands and knees.
- Place hands shoulder width apart.
- Start with your head “back in space’ and pulled forward.
- Lengthen your left leg out. Start with your toe down.
- Imagine there is a clock placed under each hand. With your hands being at the centre of the clock.
- Push with your right arm and move your hand to 12, then 3, then 6 and return to centre.
- Exhale as you move.
- Repeat on the other side.

OPTIONS:
Easier: Do not put your leg out.
Harder: Lift up your leg.

Today we’re going to cover neck strength and neck positioning. This is an excellent exercise if you are sitting at a desk and you find your head drifting forward or if you feel like you’re getting one of those dowager’s humps on your neck or if you feel that your neck is often your limiting factor in an exercise and you want to strengthen it.

First you’ll learn proper position and then once you’ve learned that you’ll put something on your head to strengthen it.

You will need a light medium sized book or a sit-fit cushion for this exercise

- Get on your hands and knees.
- Suction your head back from the imaginary television that is lying in front of you on the floor. Pretend there is a small apple between your chin and your chest.
- Put energy out of the top of your head almost like a bit of traction.
- THAT MIGHT BE ENOUGH AS YOU DO A BIRD DOG.
- But if you are comfy with that level add some weight like a sit-fit cushion or a book to your neck and head.
- Hold that weight as you do your bird dogs or fire hydrants.
- Keep in mind the setup and continue to keep that imaginary apple in place and the energy coming out the top of your head.
- Do this for 20-30 seconds to start.

Believe it or not it IS challenging!

Enjoy!

Today we’re going to use the circle band to do wall slides. This is going to work your posture muscles—your shoulders and armpit area. Your armpits connect to your core and are really important. They include  triceps, lats, serrates and rotator cuff. This is an exercise that works on getting your power from your torso and armpit areas.

- Put the band around your wrists.
- Place your hands against the wall.
- Press your palms gently out from your armpit area. 
- Keep your core and  armpits engaged.
- Relax your shoulders and keep the tension out of your neck.
- Slide your hands slowly up the wall. 
- Slide your hands slowly down the wall.
- Make sure you continue to breath.

Enjoy!

Today I am going to take ou through a Child’s Pose. I am going to show you how to do a passive Child’s Pose, an active Child’s Pose, and a dynamic Child’s Pose.

Keep in mind a passive vs. active Child’s Pose depends on where in your workout you are doing the pose. A passive Child’s Pose is the move you would do at the end of a workout. Where as an active or dynamic Child’s Pose you would do at the beginning of your workout.

PASSIVE
- Kneel on the floor.
- Fold down and put your arms above your head with your palms on the floor.
- Hips back over your feet.
- Relax onto the movement.
- Breathe.

ACTIVE
- Kneel on all fours on the floor.
- Go back into your Child’s Pose and stretch through your wrist, fingers and your elbows.
- Stretch your lats and armpit area.
- Breathe.

DYNAMIC
- Kneel on all fours on the floor.
- Go back into your Child’s Pose and stretch through your wrist, fingers and your elbows.
- Stretch your lats and armpit area.
- Move your hands to the left and then to the right.
- Try going into a plank from this position.
- Breathe.

Enjoy!

Any health habit — in the “right” set of unhealthy circumstances — can become toxic. “Health” too often becomes conflated with thinness, youth, and the mirage of perfection. 

Exercise is a healthy habit … until it isn’t. Being conscious of your nutrition and your weight can be productive … unless the awareness becomes all-consuming. The dose makes the poison. 
 
Habits, beliefs, and actions birthed out of judgment and comparison can perpetuate underlying insecurities and support a lifestyle that is anything but healthy. According to the National Eating Disorder Information Centre, 1 million Canadians meet the diagnostic criteria for an eating disorder. Eating disorders have the highest death rate of any mental illness; 1 in 10 people die from their disorder. 

In my experience, official numbers only scratch the surface of the problem. In my twenties I came very close to developing life-altering RED-S — relative energy deficiency in sport. In my quest for perfection my caloric intake often did not meet my training needs. 

My story is unfortunately not the exception. I have never trained anyone who — after they learned to trust me — didn’t confess to dealing with some amount of body shame, disordered eating, over exercising, and/or dysmorphia. Someone might not meet the formal criteria of living with an eating disorder, but that doesn’t mean their inner world isn’t cruel and belittling and/or that they aren’t flirting dangerously with disordered activities. 
 
Health is an aggregate of all decisions, “healthy” habits are only beneficial when they enrich our existence. 

Exercise is only a positive stress on the tissues when the body is given the ingredients it needs to recover. Without adequate recovery, the body will become exhausted, most likely injured, and overtrained. An unhealthy fixation on food and weight will leave you, at best, with an unhealthy relationship with food and, at worst, in the hospital owing to malnutrition.

Turn the great outdoors into a gym 
 
Amp up the walk 

Nothing is more functional than walking. Try fartlek intervals. Fartlek is a Swedish term that means “speed play." It is an unstructured form of interval training. Pick a landmark — like a stop sign or crosswalk. Speed up to get there. Once you hit your landmark, slow down and recover. Repeat until you reach the park, increasing your intensity as you go. 

 Make the park your gym 

Consider a “fun” warm-up pyramid. Pick two functional exercises based on your client’s fitness level and injury profile. A low-impact version could be walking knee-ups and sit-to-stands on a bench. A more intense version could be high knee runs and squats. Start with 2 of each, then 4, then 6, then 8, then 10. 

After the warm-up, use a park bench to do functional core and strength moves. For example, step-ups, V holds,, and/or push-ups. 

For a detailed description of a few moves check out full article on page 54/55 at https://issuu.com/canfitpro/docs/layout-may-jun_online/54?ff&experiment=last-page

Or create a circuit. Program a few functional moves followed by a run around the perimeter of the park or a cardio move like burpees. 

If you can find an outdoor playground, try pull-ups and/or an incline plank with forearms on a swing. 

Combine hill runs or stairs with strength work 

 Mix in stairs or hill running with a functional strength move like squats or hinges. What is more functional than squats and stairs? Everyone needs to go to the bathroom and climb stairs. 

Examples: 

Run the stairs 5 times. Do 2 squats. Repeat the same number of stairs. Each round, increase the number of squats by 2 until you get to 12.

Today I’m going to take you through some variations on the Figure 4 stretch. 

Option 1: Lying on floor
Lie down on your back with your knees raised and feet on the ground.

Variation #1
* Put your left ankle on your right knee (this puts your left leg in a Figure 4 position)
* Gentle press away on your left knee. Keep neutral through your pelvis and try not to shift your hips.
* Hold for 30 seconds.
* Repeat with right ankle, or progress to variation #2.

Variation #2
* Raise your right leg and circle your hamstring with your right arm. 
* Pull your legs towards your body while you press gently on your left knee with your left hand . 
* You can use a band if your arms are not long enough to circle your legs. 
* Hold for 30 seconds. 

Variation #3
* You can follow either of these with a “lady stretch”, where your legs are fully crossed as you bring them in close to your body. 
* Hold for 30 seconds.
* Repeat with other leg.

Option 2: Sitting on floor
Variation #1
* Sit on the floor with your knees raised and your feet In full contact with the floor. Make sure the ball of your big toe and the ball of your little toe are equally weighted.
* Lean back on your hands and place your left ankle on your right knee as you did above. Then use your hands to press your upper body up towards your knees. This is good because it helps you get extension in your spine. Sit tall. If you are finding you are rounding you can sit on a pillow and/or move your right foot out. BREATH!
* Repeat on the opposite side.

Today we're talking wrists.
First I want you to check and see which of your hands and wrists has more mobility. 
- Go on your hands and knees and place your hands palm facing down about shoulder width apart. 
- Spread your fingers apart. Do any of your fingers seem to NOT spread as easily as others? 
 - For me my right thumb especially os constricted and I don’t really spread my right thumb as well as I should on the mat. 
 - If any of these moves below are too intense you can use the wall or even just do it in the air with your arms forward using one hand to manipulate the other.
- Attempt to spread those fingers as wide as the others.
- Once you have that, move your body in little circles one way direction then switch to the other direction.  BREATH.

 - Figure out where is tight and where it’s not.
- Next turn both hands (palms down, fingers splayed) to the right and repeat the circles.
 - You can add a little pushup here as well.
 - Repeat facing your hands to the left.
- The last move many can’t do as it is a challenging. Don’t forget the wall or air options! DO NOT STRESS!
 - Rotate your hands so palms forward and your fingers are facing you.
 - Rock your body forward and back by little bits.
 - Try the circles again in this position.
 - These are all little moves to see where our flexibility needs improvement. 
 - This should feel good not feel OMG ow!!

As you continue to practice this move you will expand your flexibility and that’s good! We become so tight from time at the computer.

- Bring your arms back and turn your palms to face backwards

- Keep your sit bones wide.

The Hip Hinge is an extremely important exercise. It’s a challenging exercise because so many of us work at a desk and are rounded over, so when we go to do a hip hinge we are rounded  in the move instead of hinging at the hips. First stand up straight, shoulders back and imagine a tiny thread pulling your head to the ceiling. Keep your knees gently bent. Then imagine you are a book closing and opening. 

Bend forward at the hip. Watch for rounding and arching your back. You want to keep your back straight in this movement. Think of your sit bones widening. Do not let your feet or knees turn in or out. Keep your chin tucked and look down at the floor directly in front of you. Then raise keeping that same form the whole movement.

If your knees are going in or out fix that first! THIS IS THE TIME TO PERFECT THIS MOVE!

Use a band to keep your glutes more involved if your knees are going in. If your knees go out use a block between your legs, again to keep your glutes involved. 

When you have perfected your form you can add weight and slide them down your legs as you bend.
